[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] You can mitigate this risk by always assigning `TrustedHTML` objects instead of strings and enforcing trusted types.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] See Security considerations for more information.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] The **`innerHTML`** property of the `Element` interface gets or sets the HTML or XML markup contained within the element, omitting any shadow roots in both cases.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] To insert the HTML into the document rather than replace the contents of an element, use the method `insertAdjacentHTML()`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Getting the property returns a string containing the HTML serialization of the element's descendants.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Setting the property accepts either a `TrustedHTML` object or a string.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] It parses this value as HTML and replaces all the element's descendants with the result.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] When set to the `null` value, that `null` value is converted to the empty string (`""`), so `elt.innerHTML = null` is equivalent to `elt.innerHTML = ""`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Thrown if an attempt was made to set the value of `innerHTML` using a string which is not properly-formed HTML.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Thrown if the property is set to a string when Trusted Types are enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Thrown if an attempt was made to insert the HTML into a node whose parent is a `Document`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] `innerHTML` gets a serialization of the nested child DOM elements within the element, or sets HTML or XML that should be parsed to replace the DOM tree within the element.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Note that some browsers serialize the `<` and `>` characters as `&lt;` and `&gt;` when they appear in attribute values (see Browser compatibility).
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] This is to prevent a potential security vulnerability (mutation XSS) in which an attacker can craft input that bypasses a sanitization function, enabling a cross-site scripting (XSS) attack.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] The serialization of the DOM tree read from the property does not include shadow roots — if you want to get a HTML string that includes shadow roots, you must instead use the `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` methods.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Similarly, when setting element content using `innerHTML`, the HTML string is parsed into DOM elements that do not contain shadow roots.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] So for example `<template>` is parsed into as `HTMLTemplateElement`, whether or not the `shadowrootmode` attribute is specified.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] In order to set an element's contents from an HTML string that includes declarative shadow roots, you must instead use `Element.setHTMLUnsafe()` or `ShadowRoot.setHTMLUnsafe()`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] The `innerHTML` property is probably the most common vector for cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks, where potentially unsafe strings provided by a user are injected into the DOM without first being sanitized.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] While the property does prevent `<script>` elements from executing when they are injected, it is susceptible to many other ways that attackers can craft HTML to run malicious JavaScript.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] You can mitigate these issues by always assigning `TrustedHTML` objects instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the `require-trusted-types-for` CSP directive.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function, which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially dangerous markup before it is injected.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Reading `innerHTML` causes the user agent to serialize the element's descendants.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] In this example we'll replace an element's DOM by assigning HTML to the element's `innerHTML` property.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] To mitigate the risk of XSS, we'll first create a `TrustedHTML` object from the string containing the HTML, and then assign that object to `innerHTML`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define the trusted types tinyfill.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/element-innerhtml] Next we create a `TrustedTypePolicy` that defines a `createHTML()` for transforming an input string into `TrustedHTML` instances.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] You can mitigate this risk by always passing `TrustedHTML` objects instead of strings and enforcing trusted types.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] The **`parseFromString()`** method of the `DOMParser` interface parses an input containing either HTML or XML, returning a `Document` with the type given in the `contentType` property.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] A `TrustedHTML` instance or a string defining HTML to be parsed.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] The markup must contain either an HTML, XML, XHTML, or SVG document.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] A string that specifies whether the XML parser or the HTML parser is used to parse the string.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] A `Document` with `contentType` matching the given `mimeType`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] The **`parseFromString()`** method parses an input containing either HTML or XML, returning a `Document` with the `contentType` matching the `mimeType`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] This `Document` contains a complete in-memory DOM that is separate from the main document in the associated page.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] If the `mimeType` is `text/html` the input is parsed as HTML and `<script>` elements are marked as non-executable, events are not fired, and event handlers aren't called to run inline scripts.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] While the document can download resources specified in `<iframe>` and `<img>` elements, it is essentially inert.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] This is useful because you can parse HTML inputs that include declarative shadow roots, and perform operations on the document without affecting the visible page.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] For example, you can use this to sanitize the input tree, and inject parts of the input into the visible DOM when needed.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] For the other allowed values (`text/xml`, `application/xml`, `application/xhtml+xml`, and `image/svg+xml`) the input is parsed as XML.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] This is useful if you want to import XML files, validate their structure, and extract data.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] If the input doesn't represent well-formed XML, the returned document will contain a `<parsererror>` node describing the nature of the parsing error.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] Disallowed `mimeType` values cause a `TypeError` to be thrown.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] This method parses its input into a separate in-memory DOM, disabling any `<script>` elements and stopping event handlers from running.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] While the returned document is effectively inert, event handlers and scripts in its DOM will be able to run if they are inserted into the visible DOM.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] The method is therefore a possible vector for cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks, where potentially unsafe input is first parsed into a `Document` without being sanitized, and then injected into the visible/active DOM where code is able to run.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] You should mitigate this risk by always passing `TrustedHTML` objects instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the `require-trusted-types-for` CSP directive.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function, which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially dangerous markup (such as `<script>` elements and event handler attributes), before it is injected.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] Using `TrustedHTML` makes it possible to audit and check that sanitization code is effective in just a few places, rather than scattered across all your injection sinks.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] You should not need to pass a sanitizer to the method when using `TrustedHTML`.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] Note that even if you sanitize the input of elements and attributes that can execute code, you still need to be careful when taking any user input.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] For example, your page might use data in an XML document to fetch files that it then executes.
[src:dom-parsing-serialization/parsefromstring] In this example we'll safely parse a potentially harmful HTML input and then inject it into the DOM of the visible page.
